<doc id="213581" wikidata="Q2940402" url="?curid=213581" title="Prime reciprocal magic square">
<text>A prime reciprocal magic square is a magic square using the decimal digits of the reciprocal of a prime number.

== Formulation == 
=== Basics ===
In decimal, unit fractions formula_1 and formula_2 have no repeating decimal, while formula_3 repeats formula_4 indefinitely. The remainder of formula_5, on the other hand, repeats over six digits as,
formula_6

Consequently, multiples of one-seventh exhibit cyclic permutations of these six digits:

formula_7

If the digits are laid out as a square, each row and column sums to formula_8 This yields the smallest base-10 non-normal, prime reciprocal magic square

In contrast with its rows and columns, the &quot;diagonals&quot; of this square do not sum to 27; however, their mean is 27, as one diagonal adds to 23 while the other adds to 31.

All prime reciprocals in any base with a formula_9 period will generate magic squares where all rows and columns produce a magic constant, and only a select few will be full, such that their diagonals, rows and columns collectively yield equal sums.

=== Decimal expansions ===
In a full, or otherwise prime reciprocal magic square with formula_9 period, the even number of formula_11−th rows in the square are arranged by multiples of formula_12 — not necessarily successively — where a magic constant can be obtained.

For instance, an even repeating cycle from an odd, prime reciprocal of formula_13 that is divided into formula_14−digit strings creates pairs of complementary sequences of digits that yield strings of nines (9) when added together: 

formula_15

This is a result of Midy&#x27;s theorem. These complementary sequences are generated between multiples of prime reciprocals that add to 1. 

More specifically, a factor formula_14 in the numerator of the reciprocal of a prime number formula_13 will shift the decimal places of its decimal expansion accordingly,

formula_18

In this case, a factor of 2 moves the repeating decimal of formula_19 by eight places.

A uniform solution of a prime reciprocal magic square, whether full or not, will hold rows with successive multiples of formula_12. Other magic squares can be constructed whose rows do not represent consecutive multiples of formula_12, which nonetheless generate a magic sum.

== Magic constant ==
Magic squares based on reciprocals of primes formula_13 in bases formula_23 with periods formula_9 have magic sums equal to,

formula_25 

The table below lists some prime numbers that generate prime-reciprocal magic squares in given bases.

== Full magic squares ==
The formula_26 magic square with maximum period 18 contains a row-and-column total of 81, that is also obtained by both diagonals. This makes it the first full, non-normal base-10 prime reciprocal magic square whose multiples fit inside respective formula_11−th rows:

formula_28

The first few prime numbers in decimal whose reciprocals can be used to produce a non-normal, full prime reciprocal magic square of this type are 

:{19, 383, 32327, 34061, 45341, 61967, 65699, 117541, 158771, 405817, ...} .

The smallest prime number to yield such magic square in binary is 59 (1110112), while in ternary it is 223 (220213); these are listed at , and .

=== Variations ===

A formula_29 prime reciprocal magic square with maximum period of 16 and magic constant of 72 can be constructed where its rows represent &quot;non-consecutive&quot; multiples of one-seventeenth:

formula_30

As such, this full magic square is the first of its kind in decimal that does not admit a uniform solution where consecutive multiples of formula_12 fit in respective formula_11−th rows.

